    "id": "20251205_091310_neck-anxiety-are-we-panicking-about-our-platysma-b",
    "title": "Neck Anxiety: Are We Panicking About Our Platysma Before We've Even Hit 30?",
    "subtitle": "Business of Fashion",
    "author": "RFLCTN Editorial",
    "date": "2025-12-05T09:13:10.922520",
    "coverImage": "",
    "content": "Right, so we've officially run out of things to worry about, haven't we? Just when I thought the beauty industry had exhausted every possible body part to obsess over, they've found a new frontier: the youthful neck. Apparently, people barely out of their teens are now identifying their neck as a \u2018problem area\u2019. My neck at 20 was worried about holding up my head after a proper night out in Shoreditch, not fine lines. But here we are, facing down 'neck anxiety' before we've even properly experienced adulting.\n\nIt\u2019s not enough to battle forehead wrinkles and crow\u2019s feet; now we\u2019re scrutinising our platysmal bands before we\u2019ve even had a decent Sunday roast. Blame it on the endless scroll, the relentless Zoom calls, the high-def selfies that somehow manage to pick out every perceived flaw. Londoners, myself included, are always glancing at reflections in shop windows or the Tube, but now it\u2019s not just the outfit \u2013 it\u2019s the angle of the jawline, the smoothness of the throat. It\u2019s a proper panic, it seems, as younger generations join the queue for preventative treatments.\n\nAnd naturally, where there\u2019s a perceived problem, there\u2019s an entire industry ready to \u2018solve\u2019 it \u2013 with a \u00a370 neck serum, naturally. Before you can say \"preventative Botox,\" brands are rushing out \u2018targeted firming elixirs\u2019 and \u2018youth-preserving d\u00e9colletage treatments\u2019. All promising to keep your neck looking like it did when you were, well, *actually young*. Because who needs to actually enjoy their youth when you can spend it meticulously applying cream to an area that probably doesn't need it? It's the ultimate pre-emptive strike against the inevitable.\n\nLook, I take fashion and beauty seriously as cultural forces; they reflect our desires, our anxieties, our collective dreams. But this \u2018neck anxiety\u2019 thing feels like peak absurdity. It\u2019s another symptom of a culture that demands perfection at every age, pushing us to fear natural ageing even before it begins. It's a marketing ploy wrapped in a manufactured insecurity, designed to make us part with our hard-earned cash for a problem we didn't even know we had five minutes ago.\n\nMaybe we should all just... wear scarves? Or, you know, just accept that necks exist and will eventually age. Proper radical thought, that. Are we really so terrified of looking like we\u2019ve lived a bit that we\u2019re pre-emptively treating our necks before we\u2019ve even properly lived? Fair play to the brands for spotting the gap, but I think I\u2019ll save my pennies for a decent meal deal and worry about my neck when it actually starts looking like it's been around the block.",
